as a conflict, delineating the colonial history of this concept and showing its inadequacy to Palestine–Israel. Instead, Mor articulates locally specific modes of theorizing the antagonisms and mediations, colonial technologies, and anticolonial practices that make up the fabric of this site. The book thus offers five figurative conflictual concepts that are derived from the poetics of the works: conflict (judgment/ishtibāk), levaṭim (disorienting dilemmas), ikhtifāʾ (anti/colonial disappearance), ḥoḳ (mediating law), and inqisām (hostile severance). In so doing, Conflicts aims to generate a historically and geographically situated mode of theory-making, which defies the separation between the conceptual and the poetic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArab-Israeli conflictxLiterature and the conflict. 0aArabic literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aArabic literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHebrew literature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHebrew literature, Moderny21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aMiddle Eastern Studies. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aPolitical Science. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aArabic Literature.  aColonialism.  aComparative Literature.  aConcepts.  aConflict.  aCritical Theory.  aHebrew Literature.  aIsrael.  aMizrahi Jews.  aPalestine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311075168040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781531505462?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781531505462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781531505462/original  a978-3-11-075168-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles